void towersOfHanoi(int n, char from_rod, char to_rod, char aux_rod) {
 if (n == 1) {
 cout << "Move disk 1 from rod " << from_rod << " to rod " << to_rod << endl;
 return;
 }
 towersOfHanoi(n-1, from_rod, aux_rod, to_rod);
 cout << "Move disk " << n << " from rod " << from_rod << " to rod " << to_rod << endl;
 towersOfHanoi(n-1, aux_rod, to_rod, from_rod);
}
int main() {
 int n;
 cout << "Enter the number of disks: ";
 cin >> n;
 towersOfHanoi(n, 'A', 'C', 'B');
 return 0;
}
```
The `towersOfHanoi` function takes three parameters: `n` (the number of disks), `from_rod` (the starting peg), `to_rod` (the destination peg), and `aux_rod` (the auxiliary peg). 
If `n` is 1, it moves the disk from the starting peg to the destination peg. Otherwise, it recursively calls `towersOfHanoi` with `n-1` disks, moving the top `n-1` disks from the starting peg to the auxiliary peg, then moves the `n`th disk from the starting peg to the destination peg, and finally recursively calls `towersOfHanoi` with `n-1` disks, moving the top `n-1` disks from the auxiliary peg to the destination peg.
In the `main` function, it prompts the user to enter the number of disks and calls the `towersOfHanoi` function with the starting peg 'A', destination peg 'C', and auxiliary peg 'B'.

