ground_truth:
Here's a JavaScript code that implements the sorting strategy you described:
```javascript
function sortObjects(objects) {
 const leftBin = [];
 const centerBin = [];
 const rightBin = [];
 // Loop through each object in the array
 for (let i = 0; i < objects.length; i++) {
 const id = objects[i].id;
 // Check if the id is odd
 if (id % 2 === 1) {
 leftBin.push(objects[i]);
 }
 // Check if the id is even
 else if (id % 2 === 0) {
 rightBin.push(objects[i]);
 }
 // Check if the id is prime
 else if (isPrime(id)) {
 // Check if the center bin is full
 if (centerBin.length < 5) {
 centerBin.push(objects[i]);
 } else {
 // If the center bin is full, add the object to the left or right bin
 if (id % 2 === 1) {
 leftBin.push(objects[i]);
 } else {
 rightBin.push(objects[i]);
 }
 }
 }
 }
 // Concatenate the three bins and return the sorted array
 return leftBin.concat(centerBin, rightBin);
}
// Helper function to check if a number is prime
function isPrime(num) {
 if (num < 2) {
 return false;
 }
 for (let i = 2; i <= Math.sqrt(num); i++) {
 if (num % i === 0) {
 return false;
 }
 }
 return true;
}
```
This code creates three empty arrays to represent the left, center, and right bins. It then loops through each object in the input array and determines which bin it belongs in based on its id. Objects with odd ids are added to the left bin, objects with even ids are added to the right bin, and objects with prime ids are added to the center bin (up to a maximum of five objects). If the center bin is full and a new prime object needs to be added, it is added to either the left or right bin based on whether its id is odd or even.
Finally, the code concatenates the three bins to return the sorted array. The time complexity of this algorithm is O(n log n) due to the use of the isPrime helper function, which has a time complexity of O(sqrt(n)).

