ground_truth:
To find the maximum value in an array of integers in Java, the time complexity cannot be reduced to O(1). The best time complexity is O(n) where n is the number of elements in the array. However, we can optimize the code to make it more efficient.
One way to optimize the code is to use the Arrays class in Java, which provides a method called `Arrays.stream()` that converts an array into a stream of elements. We can then use the `max()` method of the stream to find the maximum value in the array.
Here's the optimized Java code:
```java
import java.util.Arrays;
public class MaxValueInArray {
 public static void main(String[] args) {
 int[] arr = {3, 5, 2, 7, 1, 8, 4, 9, 6};

 int max = Arrays.stream(arr).max().getAsInt();

 System.out.println("Maximum value in the array is: " + max);
 }
}
```
If the array contains duplicate maximum values and you want to identify all the occurrences, you can use a loop to iterate through the array and keep track of the indices where the maximum value occurs. Here's the modified code:
```java
import java.util.Arrays;
public class MaxValueInArray {
 public static void main(String[] args) {
 int[] arr = {3, 5, 2, 7, 1, 8, 4, 9, 6, 9};

 int max = Arrays.stream(arr).max().getAsInt();

 System.out.println("Maximum value in the array is: " + max);

 System.out.print("Indices where the maximum value occurs: ");
 for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
 if (arr[i] == max) {
 System.out.print(i + " ");
 }
 }
 }
}
```
This code will output:
```
Maximum value in the array is: 9
Indices where the maximum value occurs: 7 9
```

