Sure, here's a sample code snippet in Go that demonstrates how to sanitize and validate user input before storing it in a MySQL database:
```go
package main
import (
 "fmt"
 "net/http"
 "database/sql"
 "log"
 "strconv"
 _ "github.com/go-sql-driver/mysql"
)
func main() {
 http.HandleFunc("/", addUser)
 http.ListenAndServe(":8080", nil)
}
func addUser(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
 if r.Method == "POST" {
 name := r.FormValue("name")
 ageStr := r.FormValue("age")
 email := r.FormValue("email")
 // Sanitize and validate user input
 age, err := strconv.Atoi(ageStr)
 if err != nil || age <= 0 {
 http.Error(w, "Invalid age", http.StatusBadRequest)
 return
 }
 if name == "" || email == "" {
 http.Error(w, "Name and email are required", http.StatusBadRequest)
 return
 }
 // Connect to MySQL database
 db, err := sql.Open("mysql", "user:password@tcp(127.0.0.1:3306)/database")
 if err != nil {
 log.Fatal(err)
 }
 defer db.Close()
 // Insert user into database
 stmt, err := db.Prepare("INSERT INTO users(name, age, email) VALUES (?, ?, ?)")
 if err != nil {
 log.Fatal(err)
 }
 defer stmt.Close()
 _, err = stmt.Exec(name, age, email)
 if err != nil {
 log.Fatal(err)
 }
 fmt.Fprintf(w, "User added successfully")
 }
}
```
In this code snippet, we use the `FormValue` function to retrieve user input from the HTTP request. We then sanitize and validate the user input using the `strconv.Atoi` function to convert the age string to an integer, and checking that the age is greater than 0. We also check that the name and email fields are not empty.
To prevent injection attacks, we use a prepared statement to insert the user into the MySQL database. This ensures that any user input is properly escaped and sanitized before being executed as part of the SQL query.
Note that this is just a basic example, and there are many other ways to sanitize and validate user input depending on the specific requirements of your application.

