How can I modify this Java code to filter and return a list of employee names from a given set that start with the letter "s"? The set includes a manager with a high salary, a junior developer, a sales representative, a second instance of the aforementioned manager, and a marketing specialist.
Here's the Java code that filters the employee names:
String[] employees = {"Samantha", "John", "Sarah", "Steve", "Megan"};
List sEmployees = new ArrayList();
for (String employee : employees) {
 if (employee.startsWith("S")) {
 sEmployees.add(employee);
 }
}
System.out.println(sEmployees);
How can I modify this code to filter by last name instead of first name?

ground_truth:
To modify the code to filter by last name instead of first name, you would need to split each employee name into first and last name and then check if the last name starts with "s". Here's the modified code:
String[] employees = {"Samantha Smith", "John Doe", "Sarah Johnson", "Steve Smith", "Megan Jones"};
List sEmployees = new ArrayList();
for (String employee : employees) {
 String[] nameParts = employee.split(" ");
 String lastName = nameParts[nameParts.length - 1];
 if (lastName.startsWith("S")) {
 sEmployees.add(employee);
 }
}
System.out.println(sEmployees);
This code will split each employee name into an array of first and last name parts using the space character as a delimiter. It then extracts the last name from the array and checks if it starts with "S". If it does, it adds the full name to the sEmployees list.

